<tr><td bgcolor='#54412C' valign="top"><font color='#ffffff' face='Verdana, Arial, Helvetica' size='2'>Aracnakat</font></td><td bgcolor='#54412C'  valign='top' ><font color='#ffffff' face='Verdana, Arial, Helvetica' size='1'>Posted - 10 January 2001 11:41 PST</font>&nbsp;&nbsp;<a href="Javascript:openWindow('profile.asp?mode=display&id=23577')"><img src='profile.gif' alt='Show Profile' border=0 align='absmiddle' hspace=6></a>&nbsp;&nbsp;<a href='mail.asp?id=23577'><img src='email.gif' alt='Email Poster' border=0 align='absmiddle' hspace=6></a>&nbsp;&nbsp;<a href='post.asp?method=editTopic&reply_id=36851&auth=23577&forum_title=Discussions&topic_title=Five+Essentials+for+Every+Gamer&forum_id=1689&topic_id=36851'><img src='edit.gif' alt='Edit Message' border=0 align='absmiddle' hspace=6></a>&nbsp;&nbsp;<a href="Javascript:openWindow('ICQ.asp?ICQ=2042517')"><img src='http://online.mirabilis.com/scripts/online.dll?icq=2042517&img=5' width= 18 height=18 border=0 align=absmiddle hspace=6></a><hr noshade size=1><font color='#ffffff' face='Verdana, Arial, Helvetica' size='2'>Post your comments here regarding Fargo's commentary "Five Essentials for Every Gamer."<br><br>

<blockquote>
Did you ever play a game until the sun came up? Experienced that disorientation when you turn around and there's light streaming through the window? Realized that you had forgotten a meal? No? If not, it's probably because you haven't taken care of the <I>essentials</I>, the five things you really need in order to achieve PC gaming paradise:

<UL>
<LI><B>The Big Monitor:</B> Don't go for anything less than 17", and get at least a 19" screen if you can. Otherwise you're hunched forward just to see what's going on, or the screen fails to fill your vision, which takes away from the experience. Besides, <A HREF="http://www.gamespy.com/dailyvictim/index.asp?id=49">small monitors are embarassing</A>. Hopefully in a couple years the prices of flatscreens will come down. 

<LI><B>The Big Speakers:</B> You can't tell me the gaming experience is the same with little bitty system speakers. At the very least you need a subwoofer to thump your desk everytime a rocket slams into the wall next to you. I recommend a set of <A HREF="http://www.klipsch.com/">Klipsch</A>, provided your nearest neighbor is at least a mile away. Big speakers also <A HREF="http://www.gamespy.com/legacy/fargo/dongle_a.shtm">intimidate your opponents at LAN parties</A>.

<LI><B>The Big Chair:</B> Use what you want for a desk -- Milk crates and plywood work just fine. But don't skimp on the chair! A few hours on some wooden jobby that you stole from the kitchen table will leave you with a swollen ass and floundering frag count. It may seem stupid to drop <A HREF="http://www.hermanmillerred.com/catalog/product_detail.jhtml?navAction=jump&id=AE1">$700 hundred bucks for a comfy chair</A> but I know people who swear by it. You don't have to plunk down that kind of change, but do yourself a favor, set some money aside, and take your butt to an office supply store to test drive a few. It'll be worth every penny, and a good chair will outlive your computer system by many decades.

<LI><B>The Big Pipe:</B> Yep, broadband is where it's at. Nowdays DSL and cable modems are penetrating most of the country like a sensitive lover -- call around and see what services are in your area. Broadband isn't neccessarily cheap, but with a single visit to the movie theater costing $20 bucks nowdays, it's worth it if you play nightly and surf the web often. Once you're hooked up, say goodbye to pesky social entanglements. <A HREF="http://www.gamespy3d.com/isp/">Find a good gaming ISP here</A>. <A HREF="http://www.gamespy.com/dailyvictim/index.asp?id=66">Don't Look Here.</A>

<LI><B>The Big System:</B> Hardcore gamers tweak their system like a hot rod, but if you're like me and you just care about hassle-free results, it basically just comes down to getting a good processor, a good videocard, and a decent amount of RAM. That's the heart of any good gaming system. <A HREF="http://www.planethardware.com/">PlanetHardware</A> has reviews and picks for all three. 

</UL>

Other than the chair, you can find info about the best computer hardware at <A HREF="http://www.planethardware.com">PlanetHardware</A>. What are YOUR gaming essentials? </A> For the record I still use a chair from the kitchen table, though. </blockquote><br>


